00:04:27.390 --> 00:04:31.190
I'm going to start with
a brief description

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:34.280
of an underlying premise of
this paper and then I'm going

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:39.600
to talk a little bit about
the methodological terminology

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:45.780
and then I'm going to plunge
into the narrative itself.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:50.220
So the underlying
premise, my approach --

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:55.110
also, my talk is fairly
detailed, textually,

00:04:55.110 --> 00:04:58.220
so I'll have reference
to the handout and also

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:00.030
to the high points, so hopefully

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:05.410
that will help you
navigate the details.

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:09.350
My approach will be to
look at small things,

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:13.930
things typically considered
marginal, both literally,

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:17.260
mottos which occupy the
margins of the page,

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:23.730
and figuratively
unimportant by some people.

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:27.150
It is my hope by the time that
I am done here that some of you,

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:31.330
perhaps, will be persuaded to
agree with Detective Somerset,

00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:38.020
who's quoted on the handout,
and one of my mottos,

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:41.830
"Postulate that we should seek
to find one item, one detail,

00:05:41.830 --> 00:05:45.050
until it becomes an
inexhaustible possibility."

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:47.850
And that's a wonderful -- it's
a very grizzly and gory movie,

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:51.810
but it's a wonderful
movie and Somerset is

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:53.110
like a literary critic.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:55.620
I mean, literally, he
uses Dante and Chaucer

00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:59.110
to help uncover the criminal,

00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:02.810
but I think he provides a good
model for us literary critics

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:06.700
who look for clues and try
to come up with hypotheses

00:06:06.700 --> 00:06:11.600
and find what ultimately
may be the truth.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:17.720
So, the methodological
parameters, French theorist

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:20.930
and critic, Gerard Genette
has developed the concept

00:06:20.930 --> 00:06:25.510
of transtextuality, which is
his general inclusive term

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:29.220
for the relationships
between a text and other text.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:33.150
He has identified five
transtextual regimes,

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:36.030
two of which I will
use here today.

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:39.570
The first is on your
handout; intertextual,

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:44.280
a relation of co-presence
between two or more texts,

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:48.100
most often by the literal
presence of one text

00:06:48.100 --> 00:06:53.610
within the other and these
typically consist of quotations,

00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:58.100
allusions, plagiarism,
among other things.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:02.830
And the second term that I
want to use is paratextual,

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:06.490
that is the luminal devices
and conventions both within

00:07:06.490 --> 00:07:10.120
and outside of the book that
mediate it to the reader

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:15.310
and these would include titles,
forewords, dedications, notes,

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:19.060
epigraphs, epilogues, et
cetera, among many other things.

00:07:19.060 --> 00:07:23.980
And for us today the
salient example is the motto,

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:26.500
the periodical essay motto.

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:31.190
So, we shall plunge
into the narrative.

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:34.140
Today I want to look
primarily at two texts,

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:38.870
two Johnsonian texts; The
Dictionary and The Rambler.

00:07:38.870 --> 00:07:42.670
The Rambler, as I'm
sure many of you know,

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:46.500
is a series of 208 periodical
essays that Johnson composed

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:50.010
between 1750 and 1752.

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:54.890
They are considered by
many people, perhaps me,

00:07:54.890 --> 00:07:56.980
to be his greatest work.

00:07:56.980 --> 00:08:00.030
Other contenders would be
The Lives of the Poets and,

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:02.890
for some people, Rasselas,

00:08:02.890 --> 00:08:05.980
in terms of his literary
production.

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:11.600
But I go back and forth
between them myself,

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:15.610
but I'm editing The Rambler,
I have to stick with that one.

00:08:15.610 --> 00:08:16.910
And then, of course,

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:20.210
The Dictionary probably
needs no introduction

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:22.670
to a learned audience
such as this.

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:25.290
And Johnson was working on
both of these simultaneously.

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:30.890
The Dictionary between 1747 and
'55 and The Rambler, as I said,

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:35.620
'50-'52, so there is
some interesting overlap

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:38.020
and interpenetration
between the two.

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:42.920
So, we'll begin specifically
by looking at Rambler Number 2,

00:08:42.920 --> 00:08:47.670
which is on the necessity and
danger of looking into futurity.

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:51.910
Following The Spectator,
Johnson used classical mottos

00:08:51.910 --> 00:08:53.810
to introduce his essays.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:57.000
In many respects he may be seen
as following in the footsteps

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.040
of Addison and Steele, despite
the significant differences

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:04.370
separating their respected
periodical projects,

00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:10.420
the motto in both served as a
textual portal into the essay

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:13.410
as an oblique pracey [phonetic].

00:09:13.410 --> 00:09:17.480
Given the close association
of the motto with the epigram,

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:20.930
proverb, maxim, et cetera,

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:24.230
genres with strong
moral connotations,

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:26.070
the motto melds snugly

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:31.330
with Johnson's overriding
ethical emphasis.

00:09:31.330 --> 00:09:34.900
The one that I've singled
out to look at today is taken

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:42.480
from the Latin Silver Age poet,
Statius, from his epic, Thebaid,

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:48.490
and the handout should
have a prose translation,

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:52.890
"To stand still is torture,

00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:56.930
a thousand paces are
wasted before the start.

00:09:56.930 --> 00:10:02.680
The heavy hoof strikes
the absent flag.

00:10:04.540 --> 00:10:09.500
Both The Spectator and The
Rambler were aimed primarily

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.900
at a literate middle
class audience.

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:15.920
Many of the readers would have
known Latin, but many would not,

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:19.290
and even less would
have known Greek.

00:10:19.290 --> 00:10:22.320
And so the classical
models may have been adopted

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.710
to lend an aura of
intellectual prestige

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:30.840
to the essays that followed.

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:39.500
Nonetheless, many of the readers
would require translation.

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:43.590
Lists were soon provided
with English translations

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:48.970
and for Johnson and The
Rambler, the first was compiled

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:55.060
by a man named James Elphinston,
a Scott from Edinburgh

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:58.710
who began publishing while
The Rambler as still going on,

00:10:58.710 --> 00:11:02.240
in the same year,
what was called --

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:06.620
what is called The Edinburgh,
or the Second Edition,

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:09.180
in six untitled volumes.

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:14.670
And in volume one of
this edition at the end,

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:18.210
the volume one contains
essays one through 26,

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:22.470
would publish the
mottos in English.

00:11:22.470 --> 00:11:26.210
Little is known about the early
relationship between Johnson

00:11:26.210 --> 00:11:31.970
and -- I think I -- yeah,
there's the Edinburgh edition --

00:11:31.970 --> 00:11:36.840
and this is actually
a very rare edition.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:43.640
There's only a few copies known
in the world so this is taken

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:47.440
from the second issue, actually,
which is much less rare.

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:52.190
Not a whole lot is known about
the relationship between the two

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:54.330
at this early stage,
but apparently Johnson,

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:59.610
in a letter to Elphinston gave
his tacit approval to Elphinston

00:11:59.610 --> 00:12:07.090
to do this edition and
to translate the mottos.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:15.390
Rambler 2 exemplifies, the
translation of the model

00:12:15.390 --> 00:12:18.630
from Rambler 2, exemplifies
an Elphinston translation

00:12:18.630 --> 00:12:21.140
that Johnson, at least
initially, approved,

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:23.590
but later had second
thoughts about.

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:26.970
It is virtually unrecognizable
as Statius,

00:12:26.970 --> 00:12:30.320
it's more of a summary,
verse summary,

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:32.060
of the essay as a whole.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:36.550
"Fond fleeting Hope, with
prospects ne'er destroy'd,

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:40.430
Roams ere she flies,
defeated while enjoy'd."

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:43.700
Gentleman's magazine

00:12:43.700 --> 00:12:48.260
for September 1750
printed translations

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:51.560
for the first 30 Ramblers
and these are clearly

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:54.870
from the Edinburgh edition
although it's not stated.

00:12:56.970 --> 00:13:01.400
The next edition, which I think
should be called the third

00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:04.350
edition, but actually the great
Johnson bibliographer David

00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:08.750
Fleeman, denominates the
second London edition.

00:13:08.750 --> 00:13:13.420
Six volumes in Dewey
Decimal appeared in 1752,

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.730
this one also lists motto
translations on a separate sheet

00:13:16.730 --> 00:13:19.140
at the end of the last volume.

00:13:20.270 --> 00:13:25.030
But here we discern change.

00:13:25.030 --> 00:13:27.680
Johnson drops Elphinston's
fumbling verses

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:30.550
and replaces them with two
couplets from Alexander Pope,

00:13:30.550 --> 00:13:34.830
"Th' impatient courser pants
in ev'ry vein, And pawing seems

00:13:34.830 --> 00:13:38.350
to beat the distant plain;
Hills, vales, and floods,

00:13:38.350 --> 00:13:40.450
appear already crost,
And, e'er he starts,

00:13:40.450 --> 00:13:42.590
a thousand steps are lost."

00:13:42.590 --> 00:13:52.130
And then in 1756, what's called
the fourth edition was published

00:13:52.130 --> 00:13:55.480
in four volumes and this
one is also extremely rare.

00:13:55.480 --> 00:14:00.240
This is the last edition
revised by Johnson personally

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:02.800
and it had served,
controversially,

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:05.780
for the copied text
for the Yale edition

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:08.360
of the works of Samuel Johnson.

00:14:10.090 --> 00:14:16.970
So, are there any Pope
readers in the audience?

00:14:16.970 --> 00:14:18.270
Specialists?

00:14:18.270 --> 00:14:20.470
You don't notice
anything unusual?

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:22.950
Okay, you have a
convenient excuse.

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:26.510
Anybody notice anything
unusual about this translation?

00:14:26.510 --> 00:14:33.670
You would have to be a
Pope specialist to do so.

00:14:37.670 --> 00:14:42.480
It actually is from a poem that
he wrote, an original poem,

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:45.090
called Windsor-Forest, 1713.

00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:54.910
And this is from the manuscript
which was published in 1752,

00:14:54.910 --> 00:15:01.510
and there are the
verses up close.

00:15:01.510 --> 00:15:32.720
&gt;&gt; [ Inaudible ]

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:37.840
&gt;&gt; Pope is famous for
practicing what's called

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.750
representative verse.

00:15:40.750 --> 00:15:44.490
Yeah, the sound imitates
the sense.

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:48.000
And Johnson talks about that
number of times, particularly

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.160
in The Life of Pope, taking
issue with it, actually.

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:56.930
So if he were here today he
may be disagreeing with you.

00:15:56.930 --> 00:16:02.350
So Johnson was also --
you mentioned mentoring --

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:04.850
Johnson was a great mentor,

00:16:04.850 --> 00:16:07.860
famously generous
to younger authors.

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:11.600
And he helped John Hawkesworth
launch a periodical series;

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:16.110
The Adventurer, patterned
closely upon The Rambler,

00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:18.780
which Johnson vigorously
promoted and to

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:23.750
which he contributed some 29
essays and a number of mottos.

00:16:23.750 --> 00:16:32.580
One of the essays, number 45, he
recurs to the Statius passages

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:35.990
that we're looking
at, number 45.

00:16:35.990 --> 00:16:43.650
So he does it again,
he takes a Latin tag,

00:16:43.650 --> 00:16:46.340
provides a translation
that's, apparently,

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:50.150
not really a translation;
however,

00:16:50.150 --> 00:16:53.080
there is an explanation,
that's why I'm bringing it up.

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:59.910
In 1751, seven years after
Pope's death, William Warburton,

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:05.180
his friend and apologist,
who made his career

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:11.250
on Pope's skirt tails,
edited a nine volume edition

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:13.220
of Pope's works and, of course,

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:14.980
Windsor-Forest was
included in it.

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:21.170
And he pens a note,
or a line, verse 151,

00:17:21.170 --> 00:17:23.820
and I think this is
on your handout, too.

00:17:23.820 --> 00:17:26.500
So, I'll go ahead and read this.

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:30.090
"These lines Mr. Dryden, in
his preface to his translation

00:17:30.090 --> 00:17:33.820
of Fresnoy's Art of painting,
calls wonderfully fine,

00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:36.510
and says they would cost him
an hour, if he had the leisure

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:40.520
to translate them, there is so
much of beauty in the original;

00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:42.190
which the reason why, I suppose,

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:44.750
why Mr. P. tried his
strength with them."

00:17:44.750 --> 00:17:49.380
So the Windsor-Forest passage
is, in fact a translation,

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:52.530
from the lines of
Statius's Thibead.

00:17:52.530 --> 00:17:55.320
According to Pope's
bibliographer,

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:57.260
Reginald Harvey Griffith,

00:17:57.260 --> 00:18:03.450
the Warburton edition
appeared in June of that year.

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:08.510
During the following year,
the second London edition

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:11.970
of The Rambler began
appearing in January 1752

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:14.450
and the sixth volume containing
the list of translations

00:18:14.450 --> 00:18:17.940
at the end that first used
the Windsor-Forest lines was

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:23.390
advertised in July 1752
in Gentleman's Magazine.

00:18:23.390 --> 00:18:27.780
So the close chronological
proximity suggests

00:18:27.780 --> 00:18:32.580
that Johnson read at
least this part of Pope's,

00:18:32.580 --> 00:18:34.380
Warburton's edition

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:38.980
and appropriated it
for his translation.

00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:44.560
In addition to identifying the
lines as an actual quotation,

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:47.500
Warburton goes on to make
an important point, I think,

00:18:47.500 --> 00:18:49.930
how Dryden's off-hand
comment spurred Pope

00:18:49.930 --> 00:18:55.010
to do what his poetic master
disdained or neglected to do.

00:18:55.010 --> 00:19:00.000
The Dryden-Pope relationship
is a classic example

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.310
of what I elsewhere talked
about as symbolic mentoring,

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:07.890
where a writer is mentored

00:19:07.890 --> 00:19:10.730
by another writer whom
they never actually meet.

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:14.300
An older author, but whose
work has a profound influence

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:15.600
on them.

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:20.160
So the Warburton note exhibits,
from my perspective, a pregnant

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:23.110
and representative
example of the phenomenon;

00:19:23.110 --> 00:19:27.930
for it combines the energies of
respect and emulation with those

00:19:27.930 --> 00:19:30.380
that are gone in competition

00:19:30.380 --> 00:19:33.870
that complexly mark these
sort of relationships.

00:19:33.870 --> 00:19:38.940
So, on one hand, the protégé is
seeking to emulate the master

00:19:38.940 --> 00:19:41.230
and be like the master
and honor the master,

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:45.890
but also to out-do the master,
to prove that this is Bloomian,

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:50.780
a hero-Bloomian theory of
literary relationships.

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:59.140
This is the original site
of the Dryden remarks

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:01.470
and since Warburton
summarized them we don't need

00:20:01.470 --> 00:20:04.420
to read them again.

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:07.070
Johnson was familiar
with this passage,

00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:11.470
apart from the Warburton
connection.

00:20:15.490 --> 00:20:20.480
In the Dictionary, he uses
illustrated quotations,

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:27.240
or what are called authorities,
to illustrate definitions

00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:31.050
and this is, perhaps, the
most single contribution

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:35.170
of his Dictionary, this is where
the OED comes from, is this idea

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:39.920
of illustrating a word, through
showing its actual use rather

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:43.360
than trying to use merely
abstract definitions.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:47.390
And so he quotes from it
under the word, fustian,

00:20:47.390 --> 00:20:50.470
the entry for fustian,
in the Dictionary.

00:20:50.470 --> 00:20:58.390
And, incidentally,
William K. Whimstat reports

00:20:58.390 --> 00:21:02.070
that Johnson quotes 157 times

00:21:02.070 --> 00:21:05.930
from Dryden's preface
in his Dictionary.

00:21:05.930 --> 00:21:11.630
A total that represents
roughly 38% of all

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:16.020
of the 415 illustrations
taken from the entire work,

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:19.930
which is almost, well it's
more than a third taken

00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:22.070
from the preface rather
than the work itself.

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:25.810
And my own analysis shows that
Johnson's Dictionary quotations

00:21:25.810 --> 00:21:27.990
from the passage in
which Dryden's citing

00:21:27.990 --> 00:21:32.350
of Statius is imbedded
include at least 17 entries,

00:21:32.350 --> 00:21:36.740
that is just under 11% of all
the examples from the preface.

00:21:36.740 --> 00:21:38.850
So based upon this evidence,

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:42.240
the stretch of prose surrounding
the Statius lines compellingly

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:45.350
commanded Johnson's' attention.

00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:48.240
And he refers to it again later

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:51.570
when he's writing
The Life of Dryden.

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:53.520
This is also in your handout.

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:57.540
His, Dryden's, comparison
of the first line of Virgil

00:21:57.540 --> 00:22:00.450
with the first of
Statius is not happier.

00:22:00.450 --> 00:22:02.800
Virgil, he says,
is soft and gentle

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:04.420
and would have thought
Statius mad

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:11.330
if he had heard him
thundering out [Latin].

00:22:11.330 --> 00:22:16.210
Statius, perhaps, heats himself
as he proceeds to exaggerations,

00:22:16.210 --> 00:22:17.920
somewhat hyperbolical,

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:20.220
but undoubtedly Virgil
would have been too hasty

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:23.890
if he had condemned him to
straw for one sounding mind.

00:22:27.430 --> 00:22:30.420
Of course Virgil was an
important symbolic mentor

00:22:30.420 --> 00:22:33.430
to Statius as well
and this index

00:22:33.430 --> 00:22:36.710
and their relationship
here, I think is something

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:43.620
that fascinates Johnson
and fascinates me as well.

00:22:43.620 --> 00:22:47.160
Incidentally, the first line
of the Statian quotation used

00:22:47.160 --> 00:22:51.210
by Pope and Johnson is,
in fact, a misquotation.

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:54.680
It includes a substitution
of Statius's original words

00:22:54.680 --> 00:22:57.270
with those from Georgia's
384 [Latin].

00:22:57.270 --> 00:23:02.800
So what we witness here is a
case of what might be called,

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:08.030
to borrow a Freudian term,
textural over-determination.

00:23:08.030 --> 00:23:15.510
And this tiny little literary
site of the motto of Rambler 2,

00:23:15.510 --> 00:23:18.000
we find something
densely saturated

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.750
with a number of
literary voices.

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:23.640
And Johnson himself is
implicated in this phenomenon;

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:27.650
for he, in addition to absorbing
it and assimilating it,

00:23:27.650 --> 00:23:31.640
deploys it in other of
his writings, elsewhere.

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:35.420
So, thank you for
following along

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:38.910
with that fairly
intricate pursuit.

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:42.570
So what do we make of that?

00:23:42.570 --> 00:23:45.840
What's going on here?

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:50.960
I'm going to go out on a limb
here, on dangerous ground

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:56.030
and borrow a term from quantum
physics called entanglement,

00:23:56.030 --> 00:24:01.670
which is the OED quotation is on
your first page of your handout,

00:24:01.670 --> 00:24:04.380
one of my mottos again.

00:24:04.380 --> 00:24:06.770
And I'm not standing up here
telling you I know beans

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:08.710
about quantum physics.

00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:11.640
I think I heard that maybe there
are 100 people on the planet

00:24:11.640 --> 00:24:13.540
that really know
what's going on?

00:24:13.540 --> 00:24:15.020
Maybe that's an underestimate.

00:24:15.020 --> 00:24:18.470
I hope no one in here
is one of the hundreds

00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:22.960
that will take me
to task for this.

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:27.890
So here's what OED says, "A
correlation between the states

00:24:27.890 --> 00:24:32.270
of two separate quantum
systems, such that the behavior

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:35.250
of the two together is
different from the juxtaposition

00:24:35.250 --> 00:24:38.110
of the behaviors of
each considered alone.

00:24:38.110 --> 00:24:42.380
And so, I think the idea is that
what takes place in one system,

00:24:42.380 --> 00:24:47.490
it is entangled with another,
separate, across the universe,

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:52.440
perhaps, they have a reciprocal
effect upon one another,

00:24:52.440 --> 00:24:56.910
a change that happens in
one shows up in the other.

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:59.100
That's pretty weird.

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:04.280
But, I'm using the term
metaphorically here to try

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:13.470
and put some kind of
intellectual framework on how

00:25:13.470 --> 00:25:17.120
to understand these intertextual
relationships amongst these

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:19.510
various authors that
we're seeing that show

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:21.800
up in the Rambler
and the Dictionary.

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:26.760
So, in my idea, a quantum
system is equivalent to a text,

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:30.240
so you have two texts and you
take something from one text

00:25:30.240 --> 00:25:31.540
and move it into the other,

00:25:31.540 --> 00:25:34.300
it affects both of
them reciprocally.

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:38.790
In the case of the
motto to Rambler 2

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:41.790
and Pope's Windsor-Forest lines
we see a reciprocal relationship

00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:46.440
in which the reading of
one influences our reading

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:49.160
of the other and vice versa.

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:51.880
So we see in the motto
of Johnson's recognition

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:56.570
of an intertextual influence
by Statius upon Pope as well

00:25:56.570 --> 00:26:00.960
as the intricate cross-hashings
of all the other authors

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.760
that we have identified.

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:06.220
And this is not in the paper,
but I should pause to say here;

00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:13.320
it's not incidental that Pope
would be interested in Statius.

00:26:13.320 --> 00:26:17.780
He was very much interested in
Statius and translated portions

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:22.010
of Statius and talked about
him in conversation and I think

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:26.760
that Statius, of course,
is a Silver Age poet coming

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:30.700
in the footsteps of
Virgil, Horace, and Ovid,

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:34.570
and somewhat overwhelmed
by that.

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:37.150
In Johnson's account,
clearly Statius doesn't come

00:26:37.150 --> 00:26:43.090
out very happy in the
comparison, but you know,

00:26:43.090 --> 00:26:47.530
Dryden and Pope are
considered Augustans,

00:26:47.530 --> 00:26:50.450
referring to the Augustans,
you know, of the Golden Age.

00:26:50.450 --> 00:26:53.340
But in another sense,
they are also belated.

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:57.290
They are also coming after what
Dryden called the giants before

00:26:57.290 --> 00:27:00.940
the flood; Shakespeare
and Milton.

00:27:00.940 --> 00:27:03.650
So, I think Pope recognized

00:27:03.650 --> 00:27:08.010
in Statius a predicament
very similar to his own

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:11.220
where he had these
looming masters and,

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:12.520
you know, what do you do next?

00:27:12.520 --> 00:27:18.090
He wanted to -- he was going
to write an epic, he never did.

00:27:18.090 --> 00:27:24.460
The Dunciad was the best he
could come up with, Dryden, too.

00:27:24.460 --> 00:27:30.560
I think he was going to write
one on King Arthur, but anyway.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:33.340
Looking at these little
sites here, I think,

00:27:33.340 --> 00:27:37.550
expands into the larger insights
that are, from my perspective

00:27:37.550 --> 00:27:40.540
at least, worth looking at.

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:44.970
So there -- another
quotation from the first page

00:27:44.970 --> 00:27:48.870
of the handout, a motto is
from Derrida, Dissemination,

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:51.990
and he says, "Each
grafted text continues

00:27:51.990 --> 00:27:54.270
to radiate back toward the site

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:58.600
of its removal transforming
that, too,

00:27:58.600 --> 00:28:00.860
as it affects the
new territory."

00:28:00.860 --> 00:28:04.600
And again you have
this reciprocity

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:06.910
where you have two
literary sites

00:28:06.910 --> 00:28:09.940
that are mutually
interpenetrating one another

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:13.310
in the way that I
understand entanglement,

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:16.040
the concept, to work.

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:18.340
So --

00:28:22.230 --> 00:28:24.460
So we're invited to
consider the important

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:26.520
of Pope's relationships
with Statius,

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:30.660
which I just talked about,
and Dryden, his great master,

00:28:30.660 --> 00:28:34.750
as symbolic mentors in both
the construction of his career

00:28:34.750 --> 00:28:38.830
and the crafting of his --
specific crafting of his verse.

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:41.980
And, likewise, we read
Johnson differently as well,

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:46.260
Rambler 2's motto reverberates
not only throughout the essay

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:49.130
but auto textually across
Johnson's Oove [phonetic]

00:28:49.130 --> 00:28:51.500
as we've seen The
Dictionary, Adventurer,

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:53.790
Lives of the Poets, et cetera.

00:28:53.790 --> 00:28:57.030
In Rambler 2, the Pawing
Coursers connote Johnson's

00:28:57.030 --> 00:29:01.540
enthusiasm for his periodical
essay, notice it's number two,

00:29:01.540 --> 00:29:03.270
he's just getting started.

00:29:03.270 --> 00:29:05.950
As he stands at the threshold

00:29:05.950 --> 00:29:09.890
of its inception making quote
unquote, "A new entrance

00:29:09.890 --> 00:29:13.720
into the -- ," my next three
quotes are all from Rambler 2,

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:15.840
making quote, "A new entrance

00:29:15.840 --> 00:29:18.490
into the lettered
world," unquote.

00:29:18.490 --> 00:29:21.570
This threshold is Janus-like;
however for it looks back

00:29:21.570 --> 00:29:25.630
to earlier writers and prepares
the reader for the quotations

00:29:25.630 --> 00:29:27.170
and allusions to come.

00:29:27.170 --> 00:29:31.890
In this essay, Horace is
quoted twice after the motto,

00:29:31.890 --> 00:29:36.020
Epitias and Cervantes.

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:39.130
If, as Johnson informs
us, "the natural flights

00:29:39.130 --> 00:29:41.620
of the human mind are not
from pleasure to pleasure,

00:29:41.620 --> 00:29:43.630
but from hope to
hope," which is one

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:48.150
of the great Johnson quotations,
"His practice requires

00:29:48.150 --> 00:29:51.590
that the creative endeavors of
the present and the expectations

00:29:51.590 --> 00:29:54.110
of the future must be thoroughly
grounded in the wisdom

00:29:54.110 --> 00:29:57.870
of the past within the cultural
heritage of ancient Greece

00:29:57.870 --> 00:30:03.580
and Rome as well as the European
renaissance, as in Cervantes.

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:06.870
This, I think is the ultimate
meaning of his famous remark

00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:09.340
from the last paragraph
of the essay,

00:30:09.340 --> 00:30:13.980
"Men more frequently required
to be reminded than informed."

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:18.230
That is to say Johnson's entire
Rambler collection can be

00:30:18.230 --> 00:30:21.450
profitably read as a
majestic and sweeping effort

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:24.470
to collect -- to coin or
use Arnold's phrase --

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:27.390
the best that has been thought
and written from antiquity

00:30:27.390 --> 00:30:30.000
to the early 18th
century and presented

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.440
as a monumental compendium
to his contemporary audience

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:36.070
and also to posterity, to us,

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:39.530
those few of us who
still read him.

00:30:39.530 --> 00:30:43.890
And I think these reflections

00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:47.030
that I'm offering you
give us some insight

00:30:47.030 --> 00:30:49.710
into understanding better
a really famous passage

00:30:49.710 --> 00:30:55.180
by T.S. Eliot I'm sure you're
all familiar with, "No poet --

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:58.020
," and this is on your
handout, too, I think, "No poet,

00:30:58.020 --> 00:31:01.630
no artist of any art has
complete meaning alone.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:04.920
What happens when a new
work of art is created is

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:07.780
that something happens
simultaneously to all the works

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:10.000
of art which preceded it.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:13.440
The existing monuments form an
ideal order among themselves

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:16.420
which is modified by the
introduction of the new,

00:31:16.420 --> 00:31:20.800
the really new, work
of art among them.

00:31:20.800 --> 00:31:25.020
The existing order is complete
before the new work arrives.

00:31:25.020 --> 00:31:28.190
For order to persist after
the supervention of novelty,

00:31:28.190 --> 00:31:30.890
the whole existing
order must be,

00:31:30.890 --> 00:31:33.060
if ever so slightly, altered.

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:35.440
And so, the relations,
proportions,

00:31:35.440 --> 00:31:39.010
and values of each work of art
to the whole are readjusted

00:31:39.010 --> 00:31:41.260
in this conformity between
the new and the old."

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:45.180
And that's from tradition
and individual talent.

00:31:45.180 --> 00:31:47.170
That's a very well-known quote,

00:31:47.170 --> 00:31:49.580
but perhaps a less well-known
one from the German critic,

00:31:49.580 --> 00:31:52.120
Herman Meyer, the paratactical

00:31:52.120 --> 00:31:56.290
and intertactical
intertanglements we are

00:31:56.290 --> 00:31:58.800
observing encourage us to
read text in this new way.

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:02.350
Not as self-contained, isolated,
monads, but rather as points

00:32:02.350 --> 00:32:05.720
of articulation within larger
networks of interconnection

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:07.380
and dynamic interaction.

00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:09.320
As Herman Meyer has observed,

00:32:09.320 --> 00:32:11.770
"In general it might be
maintained that the charm

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:16.130
of the quotation emanates
from a unique tension

00:32:16.130 --> 00:32:19.030
between assimilation
and dissimilation:

00:32:19.030 --> 00:32:21.680
it links itself closely
with its new environment,

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:24.340
but at the same time
detaches from it,

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:26.620
thus permitting another
world to radiate

00:32:26.620 --> 00:32:29.460
into the self-contained
world of the novel.

00:32:29.460 --> 00:32:32.560
You know, he's talking primarily
about the European novel.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:38.490
And Meyer's radiation
is in itself entangled

00:32:38.490 --> 00:32:44.720
with Derrida's remark that the
grafted text radiates back.

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:48.120
The two comments operate
reciprocally, moving from text

00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:52.190
to intertext, intertext to
text, in a revolving oscillation

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:55.690
that both exemplifies and
illuminates the creation

00:32:55.690 --> 00:32:57.400
of intertextual meaning.

00:32:57.400 --> 00:33:02.820
If taken in its totality,
which is impossible

00:33:02.820 --> 00:33:04.470
for the mortal mind,

00:33:04.470 --> 00:33:07.750
the entanglements radiating
amongst all the text

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:13.170
in literary history constitute
a vast and vibrant universe,

00:33:13.170 --> 00:33:18.110
an intertextual totality,
which such paratext

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:21.620
as the Rambler motto and
a Dictionary quotation,

00:33:21.620 --> 00:33:23.730
offer brief, if tantalizing,

00:33:23.730 --> 00:33:30.560
glimpses into a sub specie
aeternitatis universe.

00:33:30.560 --> 00:33:32.930
This is purely speculative
on my part,

00:33:32.930 --> 00:33:35.500
but something I do believe in.

00:33:35.500 --> 00:33:40.150
So, the next question you
might ask is, was Johnson aware

00:33:40.150 --> 00:33:43.260
of this intertextual field
that I'm suggesting here?

00:33:43.260 --> 00:33:46.660
And I tried to talk about and
discuss over the past 10 years

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:54.170
or so, that Johnson possessed
an acutely intertextual mind,

00:33:54.170 --> 00:33:55.470
sensibility.

00:33:55.470 --> 00:33:57.020
I think it's indisputable.

00:33:57.020 --> 00:34:00.020
He does it all the time.

00:34:00.020 --> 00:34:02.100
However, he would
not, I don't think,

00:34:02.100 --> 00:34:07.250
sign onto this totality
that I'm postulating.

00:34:07.250 --> 00:34:08.910
He wouldn't recognize
the concept quite

00:34:08.910 --> 00:34:10.640
in the same ways I do.

00:34:10.640 --> 00:34:14.590
So, in a qualified sense, yes,
I think he would acknowledge

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:19.340
that there's a real
validity in terms

00:34:19.340 --> 00:34:25.030
of reading him intertextually,
but not as sweepingly as I do.

00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:30.280
For example, here's a little
paragraph in the preface

00:34:30.280 --> 00:34:32.460
to The Dictionary, which
is on your handout.

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:35.210
"I have sometimes,
though rarely,

00:34:35.210 --> 00:34:38.190
yielded to the temptation
of exhibiting a genealogy

00:34:38.190 --> 00:34:42.040
of sentiments, by showing how
one author copied the thoughts

00:34:42.040 --> 00:34:47.490
and diction of another," and
in my work, I've found that --

00:34:47.490 --> 00:34:51.080
I find that -- this adverb
"rarely" is an understatement.

00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:53.690
Seems to me he's
doing it all the time.

00:34:53.690 --> 00:34:56.630
Not in every Dictionary
entry, for sure,

00:34:56.630 --> 00:34:59.780
I mean it is a lexicographical
[phonetic] work,

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:04.370
but he is interested in this
and he is doing it a lot.

00:35:04.370 --> 00:35:07.970
So, let me conclude this talk
by looking at two examples

00:35:07.970 --> 00:35:10.480
of genealogies from
The Dictionary.

00:35:10.480 --> 00:35:18.100
We'll look at two entries;
dispeople/dispeopler and whistle

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:23.800
and we've got a first edition
of The Dictionary over there.

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:27.280
The Smithsonian was
supposed to have it on loan,

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:32.030
but we have it here, and,
well I turned it to whistle,

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:35.120
but somebody obviously has been
flipping through the pages,

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:40.150
but if you want to look
at dispeople/dispeopler

00:35:40.150 --> 00:35:44.910
and whistle, they're over there.

00:35:44.910 --> 00:35:50.510
Augustan poet, John Gay
dedicated his poem Rural Sports

00:35:50.510 --> 00:35:56.370
to his recently acquired
friend, Alexander Pope, in 1713.

00:35:56.370 --> 00:36:00.160
The title page in his
1720 version commemorates

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:01.460
the friendship.

00:36:01.460 --> 00:36:08.300
This is just the title page of
the works, not the poem itself.

00:36:08.300 --> 00:36:13.120
Rural Sports was originally
published in January 1713

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:17.190
and was republished in
revised form later that year.

00:36:17.190 --> 00:36:21.730
Gay read Pope's manuscript,
the 1712 manuscript

00:36:21.730 --> 00:36:24.370
of Windsor-Forest, he
read a den manuscript

00:36:24.370 --> 00:36:26.910
and he adopted elements,

00:36:26.910 --> 00:36:30.800
intertextually extracted
elements and used it

00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:33.280
to craft his own verse.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:39.550
And The Dictionary shows
us what he's up to.

00:36:39.550 --> 00:36:44.620
So, this is
dispeople/dispeopler.

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:52.880
I won't read the
words out to you.

00:36:52.880 --> 00:36:54.990
Because of grammatical
necessity,

00:36:54.990 --> 00:36:57.470
one involving the
verb, the other a noun,

00:36:57.470 --> 00:37:01.380
Johnson separates the two
passages and yet he manages

00:37:01.380 --> 00:37:07.530
to put them directly together on
the page so that the resemblance

00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:11.270
between them becomes
rather obvious.

00:37:11.270 --> 00:37:15.340
Neither Gay nor Pope's
20th century editors

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:16.930
in the critical editions of Gay

00:37:16.930 --> 00:37:23.010
or Pope noted this
borrowing, this comparison.

00:37:23.010 --> 00:37:27.970
Guess they should have
read Johnson's Dictionary.

00:37:27.970 --> 00:37:31.850
Gay's allusion to Pope is
at, for the latter verses,

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:35.940
denominate tyrant to despoil
the landscape in human cities.

00:37:35.940 --> 00:37:41.550
Gay's pike is analog to the
ancient kings as a passage

00:37:41.550 --> 00:37:46.300
from Walton's complete Angler
makes clear, "The loose

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:49.590
or pike is the tyrant
of the fresh waters."

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:54.950
Johnson quotes this in his
Dictionary under pickerel weed.

00:37:54.950 --> 00:37:58.760
But the two entries also
suggest a back wood extension

00:37:58.760 --> 00:38:02.790
of the genealogy immediately
preceding the Pope quotation

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:07.210
and the dispeople entry we
find, "His heart exalts him

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:13.010
in the harm already done so have
its dispeopled Heaven, Milton.

00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:16.870
That, of course, is from
Paradise Lost, book seven,

00:38:16.870 --> 00:38:21.480
describing the original and
type of the tyrant, Satan.

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:24.280
So not only did Johnson discern
the connection between Pope

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:27.210
and Gay, he provides an
intertext that operates

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:29.780
as the common source for both.

00:38:29.780 --> 00:38:33.030
It is thus evident
that used in a way

00:38:33.030 --> 00:38:36.730
that carefully examines the
authorities that it exhibits,

00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:40.470
The Dictionary enables us to
make discoveries of influence

00:38:40.470 --> 00:38:45.050
that enhances our
apprehension of the richness

00:38:45.050 --> 00:38:48.400
and intertextual density
of these passages.

00:38:48.400 --> 00:38:54.580
And speaking of Milton I'll look
at one more, the whistle entry.

00:38:54.580 --> 00:39:01.780
And there we find, again,
Milton and Gay aligned,

00:39:01.780 --> 00:39:03.940
"While the plowman near
at hand, whistles o'er

00:39:03.940 --> 00:39:06.170
for the land," Milton.

00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:09.330
"The plowman leaves the task
of day and, trudging homeward,

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:12.490
whistles on the way," Gay.

00:39:12.490 --> 00:39:14.650
The similarity between Allegro

00:39:14.650 --> 00:39:18.810
and Rural Sports indicate a
direct influence, apparently one

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:23.160
that caught Johnson's eye and
should also catch ours as well.

00:39:23.160 --> 00:39:26.310
The two whistling plowmen
and the context of a walk

00:39:26.310 --> 00:39:29.560
on a spring-like day found
in the quotation suggest

00:39:29.560 --> 00:39:33.060
that Gay takes Milton
as his intertext.

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:35.120
That both couplets are
immediately followed

00:39:35.120 --> 00:39:39.040
by dairy scenes,
Milton's milkmaid blithe

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:40.450
and Gay's strokings

00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:44.940
of the damsel's hand strongly
support this identification,

00:39:44.940 --> 00:39:46.950
so the Dictionary entry

00:39:46.950 --> 00:39:51.450
for whistles also suggest
the importance of Milton

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:53.000
as one of Gay's precursors.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.980
And again, I don't want to
pick on these poor editors,

00:39:55.980 --> 00:39:59.550
but this is not found
in the Oxford edition --

00:39:59.550 --> 00:40:03.540
Event and Dearing's
edition of Gay.

00:40:03.540 --> 00:40:08.430
So in conclusion, this
presentation recommends

00:40:08.430 --> 00:40:11.700
that Johnson's Dictionary
may be understood to operate

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:14.300
as a versatile instrument
in the toolbox

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:18.430
of literary criticism,
literary scholarship.

00:40:18.430 --> 00:40:22.830
A repository of literary
creative, in its own right,

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:26.290
quite apart from its more
obvious lexicographical

00:40:26.290 --> 00:40:32.140
functions and it also urges this
talk that paratextual elements

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:35.540
such as quotations,
mottos, allusions,

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.180
and the intertextual network

00:40:37.180 --> 00:40:41.050
in which they cohere be
taken more seriously as sites

00:40:41.050 --> 00:40:46.960
of literary and critical
activity and power.

00:40:46.960 --> 00:40:50.090
My work suggests that Johnson
deploys these connections

00:40:50.090 --> 00:40:51.410
in his writings and ways

00:40:51.410 --> 00:40:54.460
that demonstrate his
intertextual mastery

00:40:54.460 --> 00:40:57.090
of the resting tradition
as well as his creative use

00:40:57.090 --> 00:41:01.670
of this tradition to
offer new contributions.

00:41:01.670 --> 00:41:04.340
Perhaps in a way that
T.S. Eliot would recognize

00:41:04.340 --> 00:41:06.810
and approve had he
deigned to burrow

00:41:06.810 --> 00:41:11.250
with the mole-like
tenacity that I pursue.

00:41:11.250 --> 00:41:14.830
But this is, too, if I may
be permitted my own allusion,

00:41:14.830 --> 00:41:17.560
to compare small
things to great.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.510
Thank you.

