01:05:30.130 --> 01:05:33.520
you get a very different,
you know, there's a question

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:38.790
of how far back -- and
this is an old question

01:05:38.790 --> 01:05:42.210
because this comes
from my readings

01:05:42.210 --> 01:05:44.950
of Richardson years ago.

01:05:44.950 --> 01:05:48.300
Richardson has all these
quotes throughout [inaudible]

01:05:48.300 --> 01:05:51.110
and they're deep and
tragic and they come

01:05:51.110 --> 01:05:52.650
from all these tragedies.

01:05:52.650 --> 01:05:58.860
Well, the unhappy fact
[inaudible] is almost everyone

01:05:58.860 --> 01:06:02.240
comes to [inaudible] right.

01:06:02.240 --> 01:06:05.620
So, it's a question
of how far back --

01:06:05.620 --> 01:06:09.050
this is kind of a
serious question,

01:06:09.050 --> 01:06:13.860
how far back we can peel
[inaudible] understand of it.

01:06:13.860 --> 01:06:16.380
I think Austen in the persuasion
knows what she is doing,

01:06:16.380 --> 01:06:19.350
that she knows she is
rewriting it so clear.

01:06:19.350 --> 01:06:21.570
I think she knows she's using
Isaac Browne [inaudible]

01:06:21.570 --> 01:06:26.790
but what she means by that and
how we [inaudible] we don't want

01:06:26.790 --> 01:06:29.550
to start to have [inaudible] you
can have everything [inaudible]

01:06:29.550 --> 01:06:31.710
and the work never stops.

01:06:31.710 --> 01:06:36.060
So, there's a real problem of
how far the author may need

01:06:36.060 --> 01:06:41.790
to peel intertextuality and then
how much it brings into the --

01:06:41.790 --> 01:06:43.090
bring it into the work.

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:44.910
What are we going to bring in?

01:06:44.910 --> 01:06:47.990
Are we going to bring
in just Charles Smith?

01:06:47.990 --> 01:06:49.520
Are we going to bring in Byron?

01:06:49.520 --> 01:06:50.820
Because after all Byron
[inaudible] melancholy later

01:06:50.820 --> 01:06:52.390
in the book there is another
character who quotes Byron.

01:06:52.390 --> 01:06:58.540
No. [Inaudible] a real crux
of how a reader should go

01:06:58.540 --> 01:07:04.260
about dealing with these
intertextual books.

01:07:04.260 --> 01:07:06.210
&gt;&gt; Anthony Lee: Well, I
think what you're left

01:07:06.210 --> 01:07:07.960
with ultimately is the text.

01:07:07.960 --> 01:07:11.170
How do you know what the
author's intention is?

01:07:11.170 --> 01:07:14.580
And, so, you just have to
be like Detective Somerset

01:07:14.580 --> 01:07:18.010
and gather your clues together
and make a strong case for --

01:07:18.010 --> 01:07:20.260
I mean, I would ask
which line in Pope

01:07:20.260 --> 01:07:22.310
and who was Pope
alluding to perhaps.

01:07:22.310 --> 01:07:23.610
&gt;&gt; Speaker 4: That's right.

01:07:23.610 --> 01:07:25.990
The reason that people tend not

01:07:25.990 --> 01:07:28.350
to go back beyond
the Isaac Browne,

01:07:28.350 --> 01:07:31.130
that's why I said to myself -

01:07:31.130 --> 01:07:35.100
This is a new edition
[inaudible] I said

01:07:35.100 --> 01:07:37.070
to myself [inaudible]

01:07:37.070 --> 01:07:40.270
why didn't the person
quote Pope?

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:42.980
Well, because she is quoting
Claudia Johnson [inaudible].

01:07:42.980 --> 01:07:48.380
So, I go back to Claudia
Johnson and I see that she,

01:07:48.380 --> 01:07:52.090
very deliberately,
quotes [inaudible].

01:07:52.090 --> 01:07:56.900
Before her, Chapman did.

01:07:56.900 --> 01:08:00.750
Now, Chapman [inaudible].

01:08:00.750 --> 01:08:04.050
There's a real crux of how
you're going to read the book,

01:08:04.050 --> 01:08:05.820
how you're going to regard it
[inaudible] is very important,

01:08:05.820 --> 01:08:08.710
but the problem is in
trying to understand

01:08:08.710 --> 01:08:10.300
where it ends and
where it begins.

01:08:10.300 --> 01:08:13.880
You see the same thing in films.

01:08:13.880 --> 01:08:15.180
Films are intertextual
[inaudible]

01:08:15.180 --> 01:08:17.420
and how far that can go.

01:08:17.420 --> 01:08:19.820
&gt;&gt; These notes are part
of the current text.

01:08:19.820 --> 01:08:25.070
&gt;&gt; Speaker 4: Well,
yes, they're all

01:08:25.070 --> 01:08:29.620
in current text, that's right.

01:08:29.620 --> 01:08:31.860
And, originally, of course,

01:08:31.860 --> 01:08:37.780
you just had Isaac Browne
[inaudible] you have Sylvia

01:08:37.780 --> 01:08:39.080
Johnson [inaudible].

01:08:39.080 --> 01:08:40.380
[Laughter]

01:08:40.380 --> 01:08:41.680
&gt;&gt; Anthony Lee: That
reminds me of something

01:08:41.680 --> 01:08:42.980
that this young lady mentioned.

01:08:42.980 --> 01:08:50.060
Johnson's edition of
Shakespeare, 1765,

01:08:50.060 --> 01:08:55.720
he takes notes from earlier
commentators from [inaudible],

01:08:55.720 --> 01:09:00.310
from Pope, Warburton,
and he incorporates them

01:09:00.310 --> 01:09:03.440
into his notes with
his own comment.

01:09:03.440 --> 01:09:06.100
So, you have this kind of
heteroglossia [phonetic]

01:09:06.100 --> 01:09:09.190
of the voices that
are at the margins

01:09:09.190 --> 01:09:11.600
of his Shakespeare edition,

01:09:11.600 --> 01:09:16.090
these dialogical exchanges
amongst different critics.

01:09:16.090 --> 01:09:18.050
And sometimes he'll
comment and say, you know,

01:09:18.050 --> 01:09:20.960
enough, like, this is it.

01:09:20.960 --> 01:09:23.110
I said I'll tell you what it is.

01:09:23.110 --> 01:09:27.200
But, more often than not,
he just lets the reader sort

01:09:27.200 --> 01:09:30.220
of fend for herself
or himself and try

01:09:30.220 --> 01:09:34.200
to decide who is right here.

01:09:34.200 --> 01:09:38.740
And that's another form
of intertextuality.

01:09:38.740 --> 01:09:43.390
In my reading of Johnson,
that's not entirely dissimilar

01:09:43.390 --> 01:09:46.900
to the use of authorities
in the Dictionary.

01:09:46.900 --> 01:09:49.780
They are there and
the reader is invited

01:09:49.780 --> 01:09:51.240
to do something with them.

01:09:51.240 --> 01:09:54.780
&gt;&gt; Speaker 4: At some point
[inaudible] is there a text

01:09:54.780 --> 01:09:58.960
in the house and you
need to decide what it is

01:09:58.960 --> 01:10:03.660
that you have there is
all I'm really saying.

01:10:03.660 --> 01:10:07.030
Another example I had
recently where another,

01:10:07.030 --> 01:10:08.330
a new dispute [inaudible]

01:10:08.330 --> 01:10:14.510
and the act was trying
to remember it.

01:10:14.510 --> 01:10:17.680
But a new recent
[inaudible] genuine

01:10:17.680 --> 01:10:22.580
and we should take
them seriously

01:10:22.580 --> 01:10:29.350
and we should read them
[inaudible] other versions

01:10:29.350 --> 01:10:33.740
of Hamlet.

01:10:33.740 --> 01:10:39.310
So there comes a point where
you have to say, well no,

01:10:39.310 --> 01:10:42.110
[inaudible] another
area of [inaudible].

01:10:42.110 --> 01:10:45.340
Austen likes to hide her tracks.

01:10:45.340 --> 01:10:48.250
That's one of the reasons you
have a hard time is she doesn't

01:10:48.250 --> 01:10:52.050
want you to know all the
time who she's quoting.

01:10:52.050 --> 01:10:55.940
&gt;&gt; Anthony Lee: I understand
your urge and information

01:10:55.940 --> 01:10:59.240
and trying to arrive at
some sense of stability.

01:10:59.240 --> 01:11:03.210
Eventually, if you're going
to write a paper, or a chapter

01:11:03.210 --> 01:11:07.010
on something, you can't go
into this infinite regress.

01:11:07.010 --> 01:11:09.500
I mean, you have to
decide what to include

01:11:09.500 --> 01:11:11.020
and what not to include.

01:11:11.020 --> 01:11:16.100
But that infinite regress is
exactly what I was suggesting is

01:11:16.100 --> 01:11:22.600
the truth of it behind the
realm of the text that we have.

01:11:22.600 --> 01:11:27.740
There is this universe
that I imagine possibly

01:11:27.740 --> 01:11:31.900
and I think that's equally
exciting as well as trying

01:11:31.900 --> 01:11:35.040
to provide some stable notion.

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:36.340
&gt;&gt; Speaker 4: That's
what I was thinking.

01:11:36.340 --> 01:11:39.850
This is Johnson who quotes
Shakespeare [inaudible] there is

01:11:39.850 --> 01:11:48.130
