01:12:04.620 --> 01:12:09.820
So now we have this stable text.

01:12:09.820 --> 01:12:11.590
[Laughter]

01:12:11.590 --> 01:12:13.310
&gt;&gt; Anthony Lee: [Inaudible]
There's another question.

01:12:13.310 --> 01:12:14.610
I will say this.

01:12:14.610 --> 01:12:18.400
If you go back and look at
Edmond Malone and Johnson

01:12:18.400 --> 01:12:20.940
and George Stevens,
and Warburton,

01:12:20.940 --> 01:12:24.550
and look at their notes and
how they're arguing commas

01:12:24.550 --> 01:12:27.600
and various things and
you look at a modern text,

01:12:27.600 --> 01:12:33.060
say Bevington's edition and
it seems like it is stable.

01:12:33.060 --> 01:12:34.360
But it's not.

01:12:34.360 --> 01:12:38.420
It's not. That's an illusion
of the fixity of the print

01:12:38.420 --> 01:12:39.980
on the text makes you think.

01:12:39.980 --> 01:12:42.620
If you're an undergraduate,
this is what it is.

01:12:42.620 --> 01:12:45.800
Not necessarily.

01:12:45.800 --> 01:12:47.110
&gt;&gt; Speaker 5: This
makes me think

01:12:47.110 --> 01:12:52.670
that the perceptive
student who is accused

01:12:52.670 --> 01:12:56.720
